('computer-science:1-5-2-utility-software:misc:a87d41b4', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-5-2-utility-software', '1.5.2 Utility Software', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Confusing utility software with the operating system or with applications.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The <strong>operating system</strong> manages the whole computer; <strong>applications</strong> are for the user''s own tasks; <strong>utility software</strong> is a set of smaller <strong>system</strong> tools that <strong>maintain and optimise</strong> the computer (defrag, compression, backup, etc.). They are all software, but they do different jobs.</p>", "question": "How is utility software different from an application such as a photo editor?", "options": ["There is no real difference at all, because a photo editor is simply one very common everyday example of utility software", "Utility software maintains and optimises the computer itself, while an application is for the user''s own tasks", "Utility software is a physical part of the computer, whereas an application is a piece of software", "Utility software can only ever run while the computer is not connected to the internet in any way at all"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Utilities are system tools that look after the computer; applications like a photo editor are for the user''s own tasks."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-5-2-utility-software:misc:1d88bb09', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-5-2-utility-software', '1.5.2 Utility Software', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking an incremental backup copies everything, just like a full backup.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> An <strong>incremental</strong> backup copies <strong>only the files that have changed</strong> since the last backup — that is exactly why it is <strong>faster</strong> and uses <strong>less storage</strong>. A <strong>full</strong> backup is the one that copies everything every time.</p>", "question": "Why is an incremental backup faster than a full backup?", "options": ["Because an incremental backup quietly skips any files that it decides are not really that important to the user", "Because an incremental backup only copies the files that have changed since the last backup, not everything", "Because an incremental backup compresses every single file down to almost nothing before it starts copying them", "Because an incremental backup is always carried out while the computer is switched off, which makes it much quicker"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "An incremental backup only copies what has changed since the last backup, so there is far less data to copy than a full backup."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-5-2-utility-software:misc:51a50684', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-5-2-utility-software', '1.5.2 Utility Software', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Assuming defragmentation should be run regularly on every drive, including SSDs.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Defragmentation helps a <strong>magnetic hard disk drive (HDD)</strong>, because it has a <strong>moving read/write head</strong> that benefits from files being together. A <strong>solid state drive (SSD)</strong> has <strong>no moving parts</strong>, so defragmenting it gives little benefit and can cause unnecessary wear.</p>", "question": "Why is defragmentation not usually needed on a solid state drive (SSD)?", "options": ["Because a solid state drive is far too small to ever store enough files for it to become fragmented at all", "Because an SSD has no moving read/write head, so storing files together gives little speed benefit", "Because solid state drives are not able to run any kind of utility software of any sort whatsoever", "Because the files on a solid state drive are automatically encrypted, which stops them fragmenting"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Defragmentation speeds up drives with a moving head (HDDs); an SSD has no moving parts, so reorganising files gives little benefit."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-5-2-utility-software:misc:322ba2ee', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-5-2-utility-software', '1.5.2 Utility Software', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Mixing up the system information utility with the diagnosis utility.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A <strong>system information</strong> utility <strong>reports what the computer has</strong> — its processor, RAM, OS version, free storage. A <strong>diagnosis</strong> utility <strong>finds what is wrong</strong> — testing the system for faults and errors and reporting them. One describes the setup; the other troubleshoots problems.</p>", "question": "Which utility would you use to find out what is causing a hardware fault on a computer?", "options": ["A system information utility, because it lists the processor and the amount of RAM the computer has fitted", "A diagnosis utility, because it tests the system for faults and errors and reports what is wrong", "A data compression utility, because it makes the faulty files small enough for the computer to cope with", "A backup utility, because it keeps a spare copy of the files while the hardware fault is being investigated"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "A diagnosis utility tests for and reports faults. A system information utility only reports the specification, not what is wrong."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-5-2-utility-software:tips:8ebdad45', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-5-2-utility-software', '1.5.2 Utility Software', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — The signature question: why files load faster after defragmentation", "reading": "<p>This is the single most common question on the topic — usually <em>\"Explain why the computer can access files faster after defragmentation\"</em> [3 marks]. It wants the <strong>mechanism</strong>, as a chain:</p>\n<p><strong>❌ 1 mark:</strong> \"Because defragmentation makes the computer faster.\"</p>\n<ul><li>True but empty — it just repeats the question without explaining <em>why</em>.</li></ul>\n<p><strong>✅ 3 marks:</strong> \"Before defragmentation the file is <strong>fragmented</strong>, so its pieces are <strong>scattered</strong> across the disk <strong>(1)</strong>. Defragmentation reorganises the disk so all the pieces of the file are stored <strong>together (contiguously)</strong> <strong>(1)</strong>. This means the read/write head has to <strong>move less</strong> to read the whole file, so it is accessed faster <strong>(1)</strong>.\"</p>\n<p><strong>Key words examiners want:</strong> fragments <strong>scattered</strong> → stored <strong>together/contiguously</strong> → read/write head <strong>moves less</strong>. Don''t say defragmentation \"adds free space\" or \"speeds up the disk\" — that loses marks.</p>", "question": "In the ''why is access faster after defragmentation'' question, which point earns a mark?", "options": ["That defragmentation permanently increases the total amount of free storage space available on the hard disk", "That each file''s pieces are then stored together, so the read/write head has to move less to read the file", "That the hard disk is made to physically spin around at a noticeably higher speed than it did before", "That all rarely used files are deleted during defragmentation so there is less for the computer to search"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The mark is for the mechanism: pieces stored together means the read/write head moves less. ''Adds free space'' and ''spins faster'' are wrong."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-5-2-utility-software:tips:37f349e0', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-5-2-utility-software', '1.5.2 Utility Software', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Full vs incremental — the ''justify your choice'' question", "reading": "<p>Questions often give a scenario and ask which backup method to use, <strong>justifying your choice</strong>, or to explain why someone uses <strong>both</strong>. You get the marks for the <strong>trade-offs</strong>, not just the definitions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Full backup</strong> — copies <strong>everything</strong>; complete and simple to restore, but <strong>slow</strong> and uses <strong>lots of storage</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Incremental backup</strong> — copies <strong>only what changed</strong>; <strong>fast</strong> and <strong>storage-light</strong>, but needs a full backup first and is more complex to restore (you need the full backup <strong>plus every increment</strong>).</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Using both:</strong> an occasional full backup gives a complete base, and quick incremental backups in between keep it up to date without copying everything every time. Always <strong>link your reasons to the scenario</strong> (how often data changes, how much storage they have).</p>", "question": "Why might someone perform a full backup occasionally and incremental backups in between?", "options": ["Because incremental backups do not actually save any real data, so a full backup is always needed as a backup to them", "Because the full backup gives a complete base while the fast incremental backups keep it up to date with less storage", "Because a full backup can only ever be restored if an incremental backup of the very same data was made first", "Because incremental backups automatically delete the full backup once they have finished running each night"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "A full backup provides a complete base; incremental backups then capture changes quickly using little storage — the reason to combine them."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-5-2-utility-software:tips:2b260733', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-5-2-utility-software', '1.5.2 Utility Software', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Sort utilities by purpose — and know the definition trap", "reading": "<p>Two things get tested a lot here. First, <strong>classifying</strong> utilities (often a tick-grid):</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Security</strong> → anti-malware, firewall, encryption.</li>\n<li><strong>Disk organisation / maintenance</strong> → defragmentation, data compression, file transfer.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Second, the <strong>definition trap</strong>: \"State the need for utility software\" wants the <em>general purpose</em> — to <strong>maintain and optimise the computer</strong> (keep it secure, organised and running well) — <strong>not</strong> just naming one utility like \"defragmentation\". Name the role, then you can give an example.</p>\n<p>And remember: a utility is <strong>system software</strong>, never application software.</p>", "question": "A question asks you to ''state the need for utility software''. What kind of answer earns the mark?", "options": ["Simply naming one specific utility, such as ''defragmentation'', without saying anything at all about what it is for", "Saying that it is needed to maintain and optimise the computer, keeping it running well", "Explaining in detail exactly how the read/write head moves across the surface of a magnetic hard disk drive", "Listing the full technical specification of the computer, including its processor model and amount of RAM"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "''The need'' means the general purpose — maintaining and optimising the computer. Just naming a single utility does not answer why utility software is needed."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-5-2-utility-software:fib:6f73617a', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-5-2-utility-software', '1.5.2 Utility Software', 'fib', 'fib', 1, '{"question": "Utility software is a type of _____ software that helps to maintain and optimise the computer.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["compression", "system", "full", "incremental"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "system"}}'::jsonb),
